| align=\"right\" | 4,836\n| align=\"right\" | 0.10%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\"| '''Majority'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,363,019'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''29.52%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 9.06%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''4,616,836'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.00%'''\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| colspan=\"6\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Hold'''\n|}\n\nIn addition to the parties fielding candidates, New York's [[electoral fusion]] laws allow parties to cross-endorse candidates. The [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]] and [[Working Families Party of New York|Working Families Party]] cross-endorsed Andrew Cuomo, while the [[Conservative Party of New York|Conservative Party]] and [[Taxpayers Party of New York|Taxpayers Party]] cross-endorsed Carl Paladino. The Independence Party line received 146,648 votes (5.0% of Cuomo's total, and 3.2% of the statewide total) and the Working Families line received 154,853 votes (5.3% and 3.4%), with the Democratic line receiving the remaining 2,610,220 votes (89.6% and 56.5%). The Conservative line received 232,281 votes (15.0% of Paladino's total, and 5.0% of the statewide total) and the Taxpayers line received 25,821 votes (1.5% and 0.6%), with the Republican line receiving the remaining 1,290,082 votes (83.3% and 27.1%).\n\n==== 2014 ====\n{{see also|2014 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo sought reelection in 2014, with former U.S. Representative Kathy Hochul as his new running mate. On March 5, 2014, [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[County Executive|County executive]] [[Rob Astorino]] announced that he would run on the Republican ticket against Cuomo for governor.<ref name=\"Astorino\">{{cite news|last=McKinley |first=Jesse | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/06/nyregion/astorino-bid-for-new-york-governor.html|title=Westchester Leader Opens Bid to Deny Cuomo a Second Term|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> Law professors [[Zephyr Teachout]] and [[Tim Wu]] challenged the Cuomo\u2013Hochul ticket in the Democratic primary election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.firedoglake.com/2014/09/10/cuomo-spent-nearly-40-times-more-than-teachout-to-win-primary/|title=Cuomo Spent Nearly 40 Times More Than Teachout To Win Primary|work=Shadowproof}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/election-night-stub/|title=Cuomo Wins Democratic Primary|publisher=WNYC}}</ref>\u2014capturing 34% of the vote on the gubernatorial line (Wu drew 40.1% as lieutenant governor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014-ny-state/|title=Election Results \u2013 2014 NY State Primary \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/zephyr-teachout-primary-loss-air-victory-party-article-1.1934371|title=Zephyr Teachout's primary election loss has air of a victory party, Annie Karni, NYTimes, 10 Sept. 2014|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, Cuomo was re-elected for a second term with 54% of the vote,<ref name=Kaplan141104>{{cite news |last=Kaplan |first=Thomas |date=November 4, 2014 |title=Andrew Cuomo Is Re-elected New York Governor, but Loses Clout |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-is-re-elected-governor-of-new-york.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=January 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Election-Day-2014-New-York-Governor-Andrew-Cuomo-Rob-Astorino-Vote-281478431.html|title=Andrew Cuomo Wins Re-election in NY Governor's Race|work=NBC New York}}</ref> while Astorino received 40.6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014/|title=Election 2014 \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = New York Democratic gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref name=primaryresults>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/Primary/2014StateLocalPrimaryElectionResults.pdf |title=2014 State Local Primary Results |publisher=New York State Board Of Elections |accessdate=October 25, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031122737/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/Primary/2014StateLocalPrimaryElectionResults.pdf |archivedate=October 31, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Andrew Cuomo\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 361,380\n| percentage = 62.92\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Zephyr Teachout]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 192,210\n| percentage = 33.47\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Randy Credico]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 20,760\n| percentage = 3.61\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 594,287\n| percentage= 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = New York Democratic lieutenant gubernatorial primary results, 2014<ref name=primaryresults />\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Kathy Hochul]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 329,089\n| percentage = 60.20\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Tim Wu]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 217,614\n| percentage = 39.80\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 546,703\n| percentage= 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nDespite a low voter turnout, Cuomo won the general election by a comfortable margin; however, his margin of victory was smaller than it had been in his 2010 victory. Astorino won most of upstate New York, but was overwhelmed in [[New York City]]. Cuomo was sworn in for second term as [[Governor]].\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | New York gubernatorial general election results, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyenr.elections.state.ny.us/|title=NYS Board of Elections Unofficial Election Night Results|accessdate=December 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107220743/http://nyenr.elections.state.ny.us/|archivedate=November 7, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Running mate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Swing\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 1,811,672\n| align=\"right\" | 47.08%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 9.44%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#CC6699; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Working Families Party|Working Families]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 126,244\n| align=\"right\" | 3.22%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 0.13%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800080; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independence Party of New York|Independence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 77,762\n| align=\"right\" | 2.02%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 1.15%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#E0218A; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Women's Equality Party (New York)|Women's Equality]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 53,802\n| align=\"right\" | 1.41%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|-\n! style=\"ba